<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2006, &ldquo;Ontology, Reduction,
Emergence: A General Frame&rdquo;, <em>Synthese</em>, 151(3):
313&ndash;323. doi:10.1007/s11229-006-9011-6</li>

<li>Nagel, Ernest, 1949, &ldquo;The Meaning of Reduction in the
Natural Sciences&rdquo;, in <em>Science And Civilization</em>, Robert
C. Stauffer (ed.), Madison, WI: University Of Wisconsin Press,
99&ndash;138 (ch. 4).</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1961, <em>The Structure of Science:
Problems in the Logic of Scientific Explanation</em>, New York:
Harcourt, Brace &amp; World.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1970, &ldquo;Issues in the Logic of
Reductive Explanations&rdquo;, in <em>Mind, Science, and History</em>,
Howard Evans Kiefer and Milton K. Munitz (eds.), (Contemporary
Philosophic Thought 2), Albany, NY: State University of New York
Press, 117&ndash;137.</li>

<li>Nickles, Thomas, 1973, &ldquo;Two Concepts of Intertheoretic
Reduction&rdquo;, <em>The Journal of Philosophy</em>, 70(7):
181&ndash;201. doi:10.2307/2024906</li>

<li>Norton, John D., 2012, &ldquo;Approximation and Idealization: Why
the Difference Matters&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy of Science</em>, 79(2):
207&ndash;232. doi:10.1086/664746</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2014, &ldquo;Infinite Idealizations&rdquo;,
in <em>European Philosophy of Science &ndash; Philosophy of Science in
